write "None."

symtablehash.c: line 133: medium priority:
   Do you want to validate 'pvValue' through an assert?
My justifications are the same as above, so I'll copy and paste those.
It's okay to put a binding with a null value. I also confirmed my
justifications for these warnings with my preceptor.

symtablehash.c: line 172: medium priority:
   Do you want to validate 'pvValue' through an assert?
It's okay to replace an existing binding with another binding
that has a null value. 

symtablehash.c: line 284: medium priority:
   Do you want to validate 'pvExtra' through an assert?
It's fine for the extra parameter pvExtra to be NULL if not relevant to the function we pass in. One instance of this is from our implementation of a Stack in precept, where the third argument of Stack_map is NULL when the function passed in is freeDouble.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
What are the CPU times reported by testsymtable.c with binding counts
50, 500, 5000, 50000, and 500000 using (1) your linked list
implementation, (2) your non-expanding hash table implementation, and
(3) your expanding hash table implementation? Fill in the blanks.

The linked list implementation with:
-- 50 bindings consumed 0.000000 seconds.
-- 500 bindings consumed 0.002158 seconds.
-- 5000 bindings consumed 0.209833 seconds.
-- 50000 bindings consumed 27.148532 seconds.
-- 500000 bindings consumed more than 5 minutes.

The non-expanding hash table implementation with:
-- 50 bindings consumed 0.000000 seconds.
-- 500 bindings consumed 0.000000 seconds.
-- 5000 bindings consumed 0.030824 seconds.
-- 50000 bindings consumed 0.521318 seconds.
-- 500000 bindings consumed 37.977933 seconds.

The expanding hash table implementation with:
-- 50 bindings consumed 0.000000 seconds.
-- 500 bindings consumed 0.003865 seconds.
-- 5000 bindings consumed 0.029991 seconds.
-- 50000 bindings consumed 0.365419 seconds.
-- 500000 bindings consumed 3.896768 seconds.
